soners were given one final chance to reintegrate into Soviet society. Millions whom authorities deemed "reeducated" through brutal forced labor were allowed to leave. Millions more who "failed" never got out alive. Drawing on newly opened archives in Russia and Kazakhstan as well as memoirs by actual prisoners, Barnes shows how the Gulag was integral to the Soviet goal of building a utopian socialist society. He takes readers into the Gulag itself, focusing on one outpost of the Gulag system in the Karaganda region of Kazakhstan, a location that featured the full panoply of Soviet detention institutions. Barnes traces the Gulag experience from its beginnings after the 1917 Russian Revolution to its decline following the 1953 death of Stalin. Death and Redemption reveals how the Gulag defined the border between those who would reenter Soviet society and those who would be excluded through death.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aConcentration campsvSocial aspectsvSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aConcentration campsvSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aConcentration campsxSocial aspectszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aConcentration campszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aForced laborvSocial aspectsvSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aForced laborxSocial aspectszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aInternment campsxSocial aspectszSoviet Union. 0aInternment campszSoviet Union. 0aPolitical prisonersvSoviet UnionvSocial conditions. 0aPolitical prisonerszSoviet UnionxSocial conditions. 0aPrisonersvSoviet UnionvSocial conditions. 0aPrisonerszSoviet UnionxSocial conditions. 0aPrisonsvSocial aspectsvSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aPrisonsvSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aPrisonsxSocial aspectszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aPrisonsxSocial aspectszSoviet Union. 0aPrisonszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aPrisonszSoviet Union. 0aSOCIAL SCIENCEvPenology.